    pearls: ["Serum creatinine is a poor marker of renal function in elderly - always use eGFR (CKD-EPI equation) for dose adjustments because decreased muscle mass produces less creatinine, creating a false sense of normal renal function", "Diazepam half-life extends from 20 hours in young adults to 90+ hours in elderly due to increased fat distribution and decreased hepatic metabolism - avoid all long-acting benzodiazepines in elderly", "The prescribing cascade is a major driver of polypharmacy: NSAID → hypertension → amlodipine → peripheral edema → furosemide → hypokalemia → potassium supplement. Always ask: 'Is this new symptom caused by an existing medication?'", "Phase I hepatic metabolism (CYP-dependent oxidation) declines significantly with age while Phase II (conjugation) is preserved - drugs metabolized by conjugation (lorazepam, oxazepam, temazepam) are preferred benzodiazepines in elderly if absolutely necessary", "Brown bag medication review (patient brings all bottles) identifies 2-3x more medications than chart review alone - always ask about OTC, supplements, borrowed medications, and medications from other providers"],
